text=!WHO IS REVIEWING THE WORK%0aPatches do not normally pass directly into the mainline kernel; instead, they pass through one of%0aone-hundred or so subsystem trees. Each subsystem tree is dedicated to a specific part of the%0akernel (examples might be SCSI drivers, x86 architecture code, or networking) and is under the%0acontrol of a specific maintainer. When a subsystem maintainer accepts a patch into a subsystem%0atree, he or she will attach a “Signed-off-by” line to it. This line is a statement that the patch can be%0alegally incorporated into the kernel; the sequence of signoff lines can be used to establish the path%0aby which each change got into the kernel.%0a%0aSee: http://www.linuxfoundation.org/publications/whowriteslinux.pdf
