diff:1250838797:1250838797:=1,9d0%0a%3c !WHO IS REVIEWING THE WORK%0a%3c Patches do not normally pass directly into the mainline kernel; instead, they pass through one of%0a%3c one-hundred or so subsystem trees. Each subsystem tree is dedicated to a specific part of the%0a%3c kernel (examples might be SCSI drivers, x86 architecture code, or networking) and is under the%0a%3c control of a specific maintainer. When a subsystem maintainer accepts a patch into a subsystem%0a%3c tree, he or she will attach a “Signed-off-by” line to it. This line is a statement that the patch can be%0a%3c legally incorporated into the kernel; the sequence of signoff lines can be used to establish the path%0a%3c by which each change got into the kernel.%0a%3c %0a
